        Leafwhisper said, "Yes! It should take roughly eight to nine hours with breaks factored in—very standard first-day distance. We're being conservative because you're still adjusting to travel pace, and you mentioned the leg injury recently healed, so we don't want to stress the tissue too much during initial exertion—"

        Rootwalker made a sound—an acknowledgment that Leafwhisper was still talking.

        I settle into the rhythm: walk, listen, watch the forest.

        And the forest is… not what I'd expected.

        I'd thought it would be like forests back home—trees standing separate, individual organisms competing for resources. But this is different. The more I walk, the more I notice the connections.

        Vines link canopy to ground. Root systems visibly merge between different plants. Mushrooms cluster where multiple trees meet, creating communication nodes. The whole forest feels interconnected—one massive organism rather than a collection of individuals.

        I say, "Exactly right!"

        Leafwhisper said, "The network model is much more accurate than the individual-tree framework—everything here shares resources, information, support systems. It's one of the things that made learning human language so revolutionary, because suddenly we could communicate as individuals while still being part of the collective—a very interesting philosophical shift, actually—"

        I ask eagerly, "How does it work? The network?"

        Leafwhisper's leaves practically vibrate with enthusiasm. "Wonderful question! So the primary communication happens through mycorrhizal connections—fungal networks linking root systems underground—which allow chemical signaling, nutrient exchange, and information transfer across vast distances! But there are also above-ground connections through touching branches, vine bridges, even airborne chemical signals released as compounds—it's incredibly sophisticated, really, much more complex than early human researchers understood when they first studied plant communication—"

        Rootwalker stops abruptly.

        I almost walk into them.

        Rootwalker said simply, "Rest."

        They've reached a small clearing where several large trees form a natural circle. The ground is covered in soft moss, and water trickles somewhere nearby.

        Leafwhisper rustles, "Perfect timing! This is one of the designated rest areas—excellent ground stability, and the moss here is very comfortable for sitting. There's a spring just through those ferns if you need hydration—very well-maintained spot. I helped reinforce the path markers myself last season—"

        I sit. My legs are grateful, but my brain is buzzing.

        Scout settles beside me, bouncing gently—checking in.

        I tell the little plant, "This is *AMAZING*. The network, the guides, all of it."

        Leafwhisper assures me, "You're adapting wonderfully! Humans have excellent endurance, actually—much better than many species—and you've been asking such great questions—"
      </text>
