        I'm finally seeing it—Scout doesn't just bounce around; Scout is mapping the terrain, finding hazards, showing me safe routes. Three days with this little plant and I'm only now starting to read their intelligence—the concerned bounce, the discovery bounce, the 'trust me, this way' bounce.

        As I walk, I see the forest as society—complex, interconnected, *AMAZING*—and Scout as more than a companion: a guide in their own right.

        When they stop for the second rest, my legs are tired but my brain is still buzzing.

        Leafwhisper says.
        "Seven more kilometers! You're doing wonderfully!"

        I say.
        "I can do seven more kilometers—especially if Leafwhisper keeps explaining things."

        Leafwhisper replies.
        "Always!"

        I ask.
        "When we stop for the night—mushroom paste?"

        Leafwhisper answers.
        "Absolutely! Road trip mushroom paste!"

        I grin.
        "Still terrible?"

        Leafwhisper concedes.
        "Almost certainly! But nutritionally complete!"

        Rootwalker stands.
        "Time."

        The final stretch is tiring—legs burning, feet sore—but the sunset is *AMAZING*, purple and gold light filtering through the canopy like stained glass.

        I say, remembering the show.
        "Buddy, this is like the sunset scene in Season Three when Mav reaches the first valley."

        Leafwhisper agrees.
        "It really is! The color palette is almost identical."

        They reach the rest shelter just as bioluminescence starts brightening: a woven plant structure with moss beds, a water feature, mushrooms already fruiting.

        Leafwhisper announces.
        "And here we are—end of day one, approximately twenty-three point seven kilometers!"

        I settle onto the moss bed, exhausted but *THRILLED*.

        Scout settles next to me, bouncing gently.

        I ask the little plant.
        "Best road trip ever?"

        Scout bounces once. Definitely.

        While Leafwhisper synthesizes dinner and keeps talking about nutrient profiles and synthesis efficiency, Rootwalker checks the shelter—reinforces a few structural points, ensures the water flow is clean. Quiet, competent care.

        When Leafwhisper brings the food—the predictable gray mushroom paste—I eat it happily. Still terrible. Still perfect.

        I ask.
        "How do you two work together? You're so...different."

        Leafwhisper's leaves rustle, pleased.
        "Complementary skillsets! I handle information—Rootwalker manages terrain—"

        Rootwalker affirms from across the shelter.
        "Works."

        I grin.
        "Like Mav and Kit. Complementary partners."

        Leafwhisper says, curious.
        "You keep referencing this Mav person."

        I give up for the night.
        "Mav's from Uncharted—my favorite show. He's an explorer who—okay, I'm too tired to explain the whole thing. Tomorrow?"

        Leafwhisper replies enthusiastically.
        "Tomorrow!"

        Scout curls up beside me. Rootwalker settles near the entrance—silent guardian. Leafwhisper's leaves rustle softly.

        Twenty-three kilometers.

        Day one complete.

        I'd walked twenty-three kilometers through an alien forest with enthusiastic plant guides who actually wanted to answer all of Buddy's questions.

        I mumble.
        "Best road trip ever."

        Scout bounces once in agreement.

        Tomorrow: more.
